</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BF7107FF2213E495F8AF1E13F80CEB9D" pageNumber="7">
Short-term ecological observations were made during a week-long fourth year Honours field course conducted in June 1998. From preliminary surveys conducted earlier, 
<taxonomicName id="5F30E1046CC05EB1BC60A7789A1CE689" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B00A415A-F41F-4FE4-9619-5DA6638570C8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon farragus Tan &amp; Leh 2006" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="farragus">G. farragus</taxonomicName>
was the most common species (65% of total 
<taxonomicName id="F70E993AA253B43FC7F169151EF64A6F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D6E2004D-AAC6-4A97-9D32-DC5186F09138" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon Günther 1874:454" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gastromyzon</taxonomicName>
specimens) and 
<taxonomicName id="15454C4433EA8947C76D1319FDEC4FD0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:896D0D5B-0278-4732-B2AE-55DA94B684AA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon crenastus Tan &amp; Leh 2006" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crenastus">G. crenastus</taxonomicName>
the least common (10% of specimens); which was substantiated by this survey (based on 298 specimens).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6DDC6D99AD625FBEF8C836121FACB486" pageNumber="7">All three species preferred larger rocks and areas with fast water current. None was obtained from the small rock area with slow water current. However, none was obtained from areas with large rocks and slow water current. Perhaps the larger rocks provide more conducive spots for the fish to reside. Where the water current is strong, smaller sized substratum is usually lacking due to the currents washing these away.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="214513063242299AD6EAE0E45C361EF4" pageNumber="7">
There appears to be no difference in gut length between the three species (gut length 248-353 % SL for 
<taxonomicName id="2F131B5F5403C65EDF50ED76A8ADE724" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:896D0D5B-0278-4732-B2AE-55DA94B684AA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon crenastus Tan &amp; Leh 2006" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="crenastus">G. crenastus</taxonomicName>
[n=9], 228-350 % SL for 
<taxonomicName id="41C2A6643EA5310F3F3D111491F4AADE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B00A415A-F41F-4FE4-9619-5DA6638570C8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon farragus Tan &amp; Leh 2006" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="farragus">G. farragus</taxonomicName>
[n=12], 234-342 % SL for 
<taxonomicName id="409992DB789863A575820581E12451B2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F533E061-4568-49CE-BDBA-8DE1A37993E1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Balitoridae" genus="Gastromyzon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gastromyzon scitulus Tan &amp; Leh 2006" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scitulus">G. scitulus</taxonomicName>
[n=9]). However, the gut length is consistent with their herbivorous habits, ranging from 248-353 % of standard length (Clayton, 1993). The guts were dissected and the contents of the stomach and foregut examined with a stereoscope. Much of the gut contents was mush and probably consisted of algal and detrital matter. When parts of the gut content were fixed in 75 % alcohol, a greenish colour was leached out, suggesting the presence of chlorophyll, which indicates algal or plant origins.
</paragraph>
